    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Met-ID is installed with a database derived from the Human Metabolome Database (HMDB) and LIPID MAPS and is searchable for common adducts, such as [M + H]+, [M + Na]+ and [M+K]+ in the positive ionization mode and [M-H]\u2212, [M+Cl]\u2212, [M+Na-2H]\u2212, [M+K-2H]\u2212 and [M-H2O\u2013H]\u2212 in the negative ionization mode, along with the derivatizing matrix FMP-10 and the derivatization reagent AMPP",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes adduct search capabilities but does not detail the computational mechanism for enumerating adducts. The paper states Met-ID searches for specific adducts but does not explain the algorithm or process for computing expected adduct ions. The card's focus on 'how Met-ID computes' adducts is not directly addressed in the passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-5c00633",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "How does Met-ID compute expected adduct ions for metabolites when using derivatizing matrices like FMP-10, beyond the standard [M+H]+ and [M-H]- ions?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:02:44.608228+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Met-ID is also dependent on rdkit, a C++ framework for computational chemistry. The rdkit functionality was written in python files and turned into executable files using PyInstaller.",
      "asbval:note": "RDKit is confirmed as a dependency used in Met-ID for computational chemistry tasks.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-5c00633",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "RDKit",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:02:44.608228+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "By incorporating a priori knowledge about the specificity of derivatizing matrices and reagents, such as FMP-10 and AMPP, respectively, Met-ID uses the chemical structures in the form of simplified molecular-input line-entry system (SMILES) to parse the HMDB and LIPID MAPS and more effectively differentiate between potential candidates and noncandidates.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes that Met-ID uses SMILES structures and searches against adducts, but does not explicitly describe output of a 'predicted adduct ions table' with the specific columns mentioned (adduct formula, mass shift, m/z value, ionization state). The paper shows results tables (e.g., Figure 4, Table 1) but these are annotation results, not adduct enumeration outputs.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-5c00633",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Predicted adduct ions table with adduct formula, mass shift, m/z value, and ionization state",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:02:44.608228+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "No passage describes generation of a validation report comparing predicted adduct masses to reference FMP-10 values. The paper discusses mass calibration and recalibration (eq. 1) but not validation of predicted adducts against reference values.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-5c00633",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Validation report comparing predicted adduct masses to reference FMP-10 values",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:02:44.608228+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/scope_drift",
      "@type": "asbval:ScopeDriftAssertion",
      "asbval:drift_notes": [
        "The card frames the task as 'reconstructing' an adduct enumeration module, implying reverse-engineering or detailed algorithmic description. The paper describes Met-ID's functionality at a high level but does not provide algorithmic details of how adducts are enumerated or computed.",
        "The card's focus on 'expected outputs' (predicted adduct ions table, validation report) does not align with the paper's actual outputs, which are annotated metabolite lists and MS2 spectral comparisons, not adduct enumeration tables.",
        "The paper emphasizes Met-ID's ability to filter candidates based on derivatization specificity (which functional groups FMP-10 targets), not the enumeration of all possible adducts. The core innovation is structural filtering, not adduct prediction."
      ],
      "asbval:n_drift_notes": 3,
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:02:44.608228+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
