    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-adduct-annotation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Met-ID enables annotation of m / z features from any type of MALDI-MSI experiment, involving either derivatizing or conventional matrices. It utilizes structural information for derivatizing matrices to generate a subset of targets that contain only functional groups specific to the derivatization agent... The software is able to identify multiple derivatization sites on the same molecule, facilitating identification of the derivatized compound. This ability is exemplified by FMP-10, a reactive matrix that assists the covalent charge-tagging of molecules containing phenolic hydroxyl and/or primary or secondary amine groups.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes annotation of derivatized metabolites and support for FMP-10 and TAHS (mentioned in intro), but does NOT describe 'prediction' of adducts in the sense of computational prediction of ionization behavior. Met-ID performs filtering and matching of known adducts ([M+H]+, [M+Na]+, [M+K]+, [M-H]\u2212, [M+Cl]\u2212, etc.) against a precompiled database, not de novo prediction of adduct forms. The card's framing of 'automated prediction' overstates the capability\u2014Met-ID matches observed m/z to known adduct forms in its database, not predict novel adduct forms.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-5c00633",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-adduct-annotation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Automated prediction and annotation of ion adducts produced by derivatizing matrices in mass spectrometry imaging, extending beyond common [M+H]+ and [M-H]\u2212 forms to support novel chemical matrices like FMP-10 and TAHS.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:05:52.365893+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-adduct-annotation/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Met-ID facilitates mass matching of the intact ionized molecule (MS1) through enhanced database queries... It integrates advanced algorithms to automatically annotate the chemically derivatized metabolites, significantly reducing the time and complexity involved in data analysis. The software supports high-throughput metabolomic studies and minimizes potential errors and biases associated with manual data interpretation.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly supports high-throughput metabolite identification and mapping of m/z peaks to adduct forms via database matching.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-5c00633",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-adduct-annotation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill enables high-throughput metabolite identification by correctly mapping observed m/z peaks to their corresponding adduct forms.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:05:52.365893+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-adduct-annotation/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Met-ID, a graphical user interface software designed to efficiently identify metabolites from MALDI-MSI data sets... The software is able to identify multiple derivatization sites on the same molecule... Met-ID is installed with a database derived from the Human Metabolome Database (HMDB) and LIPID MAPS and is searchable for common adducts, such as [M + H]+, [M + Na]+ and [M+K]+ in the positive ionization mode and [M-H]\u2212, [M+Cl]\u2212, [M+Na-2H]\u2212, [M+K-2H]\u2212 and [M-H2O\u2013H]\u2212 in the negative ionization mode, along with the derivatizing matrix FMP-10 and the derivatization reagent AMPP.",
      "asbval:note": "Met-ID does automate metabolite identification and supports multiple derivatizing matrices (FMP-10, AMPP confirmed; TAHS mentioned in intro but not confirmed in Met-ID's actual supported matrices). However, the role description claims 'adduct form prediction via RDKit-powered structure analysis'\u2014this is misleading. Met-ID uses RDKit to parse SMILES structures and identify functional groups (to filter which metabolites can be derivatized), not to predict novel adduct forms. Adduct matching is done against a precompiled database of known adducts, not predicted de novo.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-5c00633",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-adduct-annotation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Met-ID \u2014 Core software platform that automates metabolite identification in mass spectrometry imaging with extensible support for multiple derivatizing matrices and adduct form prediction via RDKit-powered structure analysis",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:05:52.365893+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-adduct-annotation/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Met-ID uses chemical structures in the form of simplified molecular-input line-entry system (SMILES) to parse the HMDB and LIPID MAPS and more effectively differentiate between potential candidates and noncandidates... The number of matrix targets is precomputed based on the SMILES structure of each molecule... Met-ID was built in the Tauri software framework... Met-ID is also dependent on rdkit, a C++ framework for computational chemistry.",
      "asbval:note": "RDKit is confirmed as a dependency used to parse SMILES structures and identify functional groups (matrix targets). However, the role description claims RDKit is used to 'predict ionization behavior' and 'compute expected adduct forms'\u2014the paper does not support this. RDKit is used for structural parsing and functional group identification to filter candidates, not for predicting ionization behavior or computing adduct forms. Adduct forms are matched against a precompiled database.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-5c00633",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-adduct-annotation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "RDKit \u2014 Cheminformatics engine used by Met-ID to parse molecular structures, predict ionization behavior, and compute expected adduct forms for registered derivatizing matrices",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:05:52.365893+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-adduct-annotation/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Met-ID enables annotation of m / z features from any type of MALDI-MSI experiment, involving either derivatizing or conventional matrices... Met-ID facilitates mass matching of the intact ionized molecule (MS1) through enhanced database queries.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper supports use for derivatized metabolite samples and automatic annotation of ion forms. However, 'predict' is misleading\u2014Met-ID matches observed m/z to known adduct forms in its database, not predict novel forms. The scope should say 'match' or 'annotate' rather than 'predict'.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-5c00633",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-adduct-annotation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Use this skill when you have mass spectrometry data from derivatized metabolite samples and need to automatically predict and validate the ion forms (e.g., [M+matrix_adduct]+) produced by a specific derivatizing matrix.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:05:52.365893+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-adduct-annotation/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "A prominent addition to the technique that enhances the detection of diverse metabolites is on-tissue chemical derivatization... Derivatizing agents can be used as complements to conventional matrices or on their own as reactive matrices... There are many examples of reactive matrices and derivatizing agents in the literature, e.g., FMP-10... Unlike traditional matrices that assist in the ionization process, FMP-10 and similar derivatizing matrices possess permanent charges.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper supports the motivation for non-standard matrix support and high-throughput automation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-5c00633",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-adduct-annotation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This is especially critical when working with non-standard matrices beyond [M+H]+ in positive mode or [M-H]\u2212 in negative mode, or when manual expert annotation is infeasible in high-throughput studies.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:05:52.365893+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-ion-formula-assignment/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Met-ID enables annotation of m / z features from any type of MALDI-MSI experiment, involving either derivatizing or conventional matrices. It utilizes structural information for derivatizing matrices to generate a subset of targets that contain only functional groups specific to the derivatization agent.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes Met-ID as performing metabolite *identification* and *annotation* via database matching and MS2 comparison, not as a tool for *predicting* or *enumerating* adduct formulas de novo. Met-ID uses precomputed derivatization targets based on SMILES structures (passage 4: 'uses the chemical structures in the form of simplified molecular-input line-entry system (SMILES) to parse the HMDB and LIPID MAPS'), but the core function is filtering a precompiled database, not generating predicted adduct m/z values from first principles. The card's framing as 'automated prediction and enumeration' overstates the generative capability; Met-ID is a database-query and matching tool.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-5c00633",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-ion-formula-assignment",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Automated prediction and enumeration of expected adduct ion formulas and m/z values for metabolites in mass spectrometry imaging, with support for derivatizing matrices (e.g. FMP-10) that produce non-standard ionization patterns.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:06:12.664657+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometry-ion-formula-assignment/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Met-ID facilitates mass matching of the intact ionized molecule (MS1) through enhanced database queries... It integrates advanced algorithms to automatically annotate the chemically derivatized metabolites, significantly reducing the time and complexity involved in data analysis. The software supports high-throughput metabolomic studies and minimizes potential errors and biases associated with manual data interpretation.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly states Met-ID automates annotation and reduces manual interpretation burden in high-throughput workflows.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-5c00633",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometry-ion-formula-assignment",
