    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-weight-prediction-with-modifications/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Met-ID is installed with a database derived from the Human Metabolome Database (HMDB) and LIPID MAPS and is searchable for common adducts, such as [M + H]+, [M + Na]+ and [M+K]+ in the positive ionization mode and [M-H]\u2212, [M+Cl]\u2212, [M+Na-2H]\u2212, [M+K-2H]\u2212 and [M-H2O\u2013H]\u2212 in the negative ionization mode, along with the derivatizing matrix FMP-10... To enable Met-ID to be used for any type of MSI experiment, it was developed to be dynamic, i.e., users can add their own metabolites, functional groups and matrices, as well as MS2 spectra to customize their own version of Met-ID.",
      "asbval:note": "Met-ID is confirmed as the host software with extensible matrix support and adduct enumeration capabilities.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-5c00633",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
